		<title>Opal Security Raises $23M to Expand AI-Native Access Governance Platform</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/opal-security-raises-23m-ai-access-governance/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Clinton]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 05 Jun 2026 12:57:17 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[AI]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=202479</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Opal Security Raises $23M to Scale Identity Governance Opal Security has raised $23 million in new funding to fuel rapid growth. The round was led by Greylock and Battery Ventures,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/opal-security-raises-23m-ai-access-governance/" data-wpel-link="internal">Opal Security Raises $23M to Expand AI-Native Access Governance Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Opal Security Raises $23M to Scale Identity Governance</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Opal Security has raised $23 million in new funding to fuel rapid growth. The round was led by Greylock and Battery Ventures, with Cambium Capital joining in. In total, the company has now raised $59 million.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Opal Security will utilize the new funding to scale its operations, enhance its product development capabilities, and to increase hiring across several business units, said the company. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The new funding round is a testament to Opal&#8217;s continued growth, with more than 60% of employees joining in 2026 alone. Hiring continues across engineering, product and go-to-market. Opal addresses growing AI identity governance challenges across critical systems, alongside human and service accounts.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company stated that access governance will increasingly become the defining challenge for enterprise security and as organizations increase adoption of </span><a href="https://cloud.google.com/discover/what-are-ai-agents" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">AI agents</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> to run their systems, traditional identity solutions can&#8217;t keep up. Opal Security aims to address the growing need with their AI-native approach.</span></p>
<h2><b>AI Agents Create New Security Challenges for Enterprises</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The rise of AI agents is transforming how organisations manage access. These systems often operate autonomously and interact with sensitive company resources. Many inherit permissions that were originally designed for human users.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This creates new security risks. Excessive permissions can increase exposure to cyber threats. Security teams need visibility into every identity operating across their environments.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Opal provides a platform that unifies governance for humans, services, and AI agents. The system gives organisations a single access graph for monitoring permissions. It also applies policy controls consistently across all identities.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company launched a major platform update in March. The release introduced tools for viewing, enforcing, and managing access governance. At the centre of the platform is Paladin, an AI engine designed to automate access decisions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Paladin evaluates requests and determines whether human approval is required. Routine requests are processed automatically. More complex decisions are escalated to security teams.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This approach reduces manual workloads while improving security oversight. Enterprises can enforce policies at machine speed. The result is faster operations without sacrificing governance standards.</span></p>
<h2><b>Major Enterprises Adopt Opal’s Access Platform</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_202486" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202486" class="size-full wp-image-202486" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Opal-2.png" alt="Illustration of an AI-native access governance platform managing human and AI identities through real-time permissions, automated security controls, and enterprise-scale access management." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-202486" class="wp-caption-text">Enterprise adoption of AI-native access governance is accelerating as organizations implement real-time identity controls, just-in-time permissions, and continuous security oversight for both human users and autonomous AI systems. Source: Created by Ventureburn.</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Opal has already attracted several prominent enterprise customers. Organisations including Databricks, Notion, Cloudflare, Scale AI, CoreWeave, SpaceXAI, and Superhuman use the platform. These companies rely on Opal to modernise identity management as AI adoption increases.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The platform processes large volumes of access activity daily. Databricks manages approximately 86,000 just-in-time access requests through Opal. Mercari also uses the platform to govern thousands of Okta entitlements through automated reviews.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company promotes a just-in-time access model. Permissions are granted only when needed and removed immediately afterwards. This reduces standing privileges and limits potential security risks.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">AI agents require the same controls as human users. However, they operate at significantly greater speed and scale. Opal believes traditional governance systems are not designed for this environment.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Chief Executive Officer Howard Ting joined the company in late 2025. His background includes leadership roles at Cyberhaven, Nutanix, Palo Alto Networks, and Redis. Since arriving, he has focused on scaling both the platform and executive team.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company argues that access control is shifting from a periodic review process to a continuous security function. This trend is expected to accelerate as enterprises deploy larger numbers of autonomous systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/supabase-raises-500m-series-f-ai-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Supabase Raises $500M Series F to Expand AI Database Infrastructure</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Leadership Expansion Supports Next Growth Phase</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Alongside the funding announcement, Opal introduced several senior leadership appointments. Sameer Mehta joined as Chief Product Officer after previously working at Veza. Alex Pien was promoted to Chief Technology Officer following leadership roles at Meta.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company also appointed John Clark as Vice President of Field Engineering. Michael Kwon joined as Vice President of Marketing. Christine Ooley became Head of Product and Solutions Marketing after roles at Salesforce and Box.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">These appointments strengthen Opal’s product, engineering, and commercial capabilities. Leadership believes experienced executives will help guide the company through its next stage of growth. The focus remains on scaling adoption while maintaining platform innovation.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sameer Mehta highlighted the growing complexity of identity security. He noted that access decisions now occur continuously across humans, services, and AI agents. According to Mehta, the challenge is no longer visibility alone but real-time control.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Opal’s long-term strategy centres on becoming the control layer for enterprise identity. Opal wants organizations to be making all access decisions uniformly throughout every system: employees, applications, service accounts and AI.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">With the increasingly broad use of AI by businesses, identity governance will take on more importance than it already does. The challenge for security professionals will be balancing innovation with risk management. Opal feels that its platform can do that.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/opal-security-raises-23m-ai-access-governance/" data-wpel-link="internal">Opal Security Raises $23M to Expand AI-Native Access Governance Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
