					<description><![CDATA[<p>Red Metals, a developer of next-generation copper, has closed a seed funding round totalling $10 million in support of its mission to bring copper refining and manufacturing infrastructure back to</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/red-metals-secures-10m-for-u-s-copper-supply-chain/" data-wpel-link="internal">Red Metals Secures $10M for U.S. Copper Supply Chain</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.redmetals.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Red Metals,</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> a developer of next-generation copper, has closed a seed </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/helions-465m-raise-signals-growing-fusion-demand/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round totalling $10 million in support of its mission to bring copper refining and manufacturing infrastructure back to the United States. The lead investor in the round was Gigascale Capital, a VC focused on heavy industry and climate.</span></p>
<div>
<div data-test-render-count="1">
<div class="group">
<div class="contents">
<div class="group relative relative pb-3" data-is-streaming="false">
<div class="font-claude-response relative leading-[1.65rem] [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:bg-bg-000/50 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8">
<div>
<div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown">
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Future Ventures, MCJ, and JB Straubel — Tesla co-founder and Redwood Materials CEO — also backed the round alongside sustainability and technology venture investors. This seed money represents a huge step forward for Red Metals, as it readies to launch a huge manufacturing facility that aims to beat the effects of decades of industrial offshoring.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Massive Infrastructure Play in South Carolina</span></h2>
<p>Red Metals will directly apply the $10 million seed funding toward a $70 million manufacturing plant in North Charleston, South Carolina. The company will construct the 42,000-square-foot plant at 4500 Leeds Avenue. The project has already achieved backing in the form of economic incentives through agreements with the state of South Carolina and Charleston County.</p>
<div id="attachment_202464" style="width: 490px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202464" class="size-full wp-image-202464" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Red-Metals.jpg" alt="Red-Metals Logo" width="480" height="356" /><p id="caption-attachment-202464" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Red-Metals</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The plant forms a major economic injection for the community of Charleston, and the initial phase of its operation will create at least 45 jobs for the local population. The local government agencies have advanced the development of the site by providing approval of job development credits. Red Metals has projected the Charleston plant to be operational by the fourth quarter of 2026, a remarkably quick schedule for an operation of such far-reaching, heavy-industry significance.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/helions-465m-raise-signals-growing-fusion-demand/?amp=1" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Helion’s $465M Raise Signals Growing Fusion Demand</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Addressing the Exploding Demand and Systemic Gaps</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The business model at Red Metals is, in fact, a response to an approaching macroeconomic crisis. Copper is the elemental backbone of everything from electrical grids and data centers to electric vehicles, defense systems, and battery storage. As the recent global charge for artificial intelligence and electrification accelerates, S&amp;P Global projects that the world&#8217;s demand for copper will nearly double by 2035. Domestic American demand, alone, is forecasted to increase by more than 1 million metric tonnes/year, a market value of greater than $45 billion.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Yet the American ability to supply that demand has sharply declined. The closing of domestic plants over the past twenty years is leading to an estimated gross copper refining deficit of over 2.5 million metric tonnes/year by 2035. Disturbingly, this supply shortfall will occur even if all announced large mining projects are implemented. The problem is not a resource deficit (millions of tonnes are in the ground) but an inability to produce the refined quantities domestically.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Bypassing the Traditional Smelting Problem</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Traditional copper refining is a slow, capital-intensive, and polluting-intensive international cycle. As originally developed for raw ore averaging less than 1% pure copper, conventional workflows require the transition of materials through multiple physical intermediaries – concentrate, matte, anode, cathode – before that material becomes an industrially useful finished rod. This vast, disentropic legacy process demands an array of discrete mills, smelters, refineries, and other facilities owned by different entities across multiple continents. This incurs months of supply chain delays and ignites vast quantities of greenhouse gases.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Red Metals has set out to eliminate this problem with a proprietary, streamlined chemical and mechanical procedure. Led by founder and CEO Jackson Switzer, Red Metals has developed a sequential technology that combines physical preparation, chemical-free automated mineral and metal classification, and metallurgical refining as a single, seamless production system. In effect, the company converts copper raw materials directly into finished high-purity electrical rods in a single facility, skipping the intermediate chemical states.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/red-metals-secures-10m-for-u-s-copper-supply-chain/" data-wpel-link="internal">Red Metals Secures $10M for U.S. Copper Supply Chain</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
