					<description><![CDATA[<p>Swiss cleantech innovator GR3N has completed a Series B financing of €15.5M. The fresh financing will enable the deployment of the company’s patented chemical recycling technology and unlock the huge</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/gr3n-raises-e15-5m-series-b-for-pet-recycling-growth/" data-wpel-link="internal">GR3N Raises €15.5M Series B for PET Recycling Growth</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Swiss cleantech innovator </span><a href="https://gr3n-recycling.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">GR3N </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has completed a Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/helions-465m-raise-signals-growing-fusion-demand/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">of €15.5M. The fresh financing will enable the deployment of the company’s patented chemical recycling technology and unlock the huge amount of plastic and polyester waste in the world that is currently not being recycled through existing infrastructure.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round was led by 360 Capital, a well-known Franco-Italian VC firm that invests in deep tech and climate tech startups. New backer VP Textile joined the round. GR Capital was the sole financial adviser to GR3N on the deal. Simultaneously with the financing, Martin Stephan was named as the new CEO of GR3N.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Breaking the Limits of Mechanical Recycling</span></h2>
<p>The world uses polyethene terephthalate (PET), one of the most common plastics, with a yearly market of 100 million tonnes. The existing worldwide recycling infrastructure nevertheless remains very limited. Almost 98% of current recycling systems only operate on mechanical lines.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Most valuable for mechanical reprocessing are just clear or light blue bottles, making only 15% of the PET feed stream. </span>Industry regards 85% of content — dark resins, food containers, multilayer films, and heavy polyester fibres — as unrecyclable, sending it to landfills or incinerators.</p>
<div id="attachment_202457" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202457" class="size-large wp-image-202457" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/recycle-bin-1024x683.jpg" alt="recycle bin" width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-202457" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">GR3N has devised a different approach to capture the overlooked 85% of waste. Its unique technology, called Microwave-Assisted Depolymerisation (MADE), employs microwaves to initiate a powerful chemical reaction, which pries open and dissociates the basic elements of the polymer into the basic molecular units, the monomers.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/helions-465m-raise-signals-growing-fusion-demand/?amp=1" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Helion’s $465M Raise Signals Growing Fusion Demand</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Power of the MADE System</span></h2>
<div>
<div data-test-render-count="1">
<div class="group">
<div class="contents">
<div class="group relative relative pb-3" data-is-streaming="false">
<div class="font-claude-response relative leading-[1.65rem] [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:bg-bg-000/50 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8">
<div>
<div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown">
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Unlike glycolysis or methanogenesis, the MADE approach faces no feedstock constraints restricting its chemical recycling alternative. It can take pre- and post-consumer synthetic blended textiles, coloured fabrics, and heavily contaminated waste packages, in addition to monomer feedstocks.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The monomers produced have the same purity as virgin oil-derived chemicals and can simply be repolymerised again and again as food-grade packaging or high-quality clothing articles without compromise in performance or durability. The initial validation data also demonstrate CO₂ reduction of up to 80% relative to virgin PET manufacturing. The chemical process&#8217;s engineering basis is protected by a Swiss-based company&#8217;s threesome of patent families.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Constructing the MODUS Production Plant</span></h2>
<p>The Series B funding will mainly finance MODUS development, the world&#8217;s first commercial-scale microwave depolymerisation operation. Intecsa Industrial, a Cobra IS subsidiary, will build the plant in Spain under an EPC contract. The facilities will process 40,000 tonnes of PET waste annually.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The commercialisation project has already attracted considerable institutional support, having obtained a binding European Union Innovation Fund grant agreement for €35 million under its Large Scale Industrial Projects pillar. The firm anticipates reaching a formal financial closing for construction of the facility by Q4 2027, with commercial operation to begin in Q2 2030.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Market Driven by Regulatory Pressure</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This commercial push lands at a crucial moment for global consumer brands and packaging fabricators. As directives, including the European Union&#8217;s Packaging and Packaging Waste Regulation (PPWR), evolve, recycler inclusion set points are becoming more and more stringent. Existing regulations require packaging producers to integrate 20-30% recycled PET by 2030, and by 2040, that figure increases to 65%.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/gr3n-raises-e15-5m-series-b-for-pet-recycling-growth/" data-wpel-link="internal">GR3N Raises €15.5M Series B for PET Recycling Growth</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
